File name mask description: "0000": If there are less than four digits, use 0 to make up four digits. "0": The file name is based on the actual page number, without 0 fill. The text can be enclosed in English double quotation marks (such as "\" is about 2046"0", the preceding "2046" will not be interpreted as a placeholder).

Explanation of page range: The page range represents the original PDF document pages to be processed. When no page number range is specified, extract the contents of all pages of the source file. If there are multiple page numbers, they can be separated by "," or " " (space). Use "-" to indicate the starting and ending page numbers. For example: "1;4-15;2 56", which means to extract the contents of page 1, page 4 to 15, page 2 and page 56 in sequence. If the number before "-" is greater than the number after "-", it means reverse order processing. For example: "300-1" means to extract the content of pages 300, 299, 298... 3, 2, and 1. Negative numbers indicate the number of pages in the last document, for example, "-1" means the first page from the bottom, and "1--2" means from the first page to the second last page.

Description of page range; The page range indicates the pages of the original PDF document to be processed. When no page number range is specified, extract the contents of all pages of the source file. If there are multiple page numbers, they can be separated by "," or " " (space). Use "-" to indicate the starting and ending page numbers. For example: "1;4-15;2 56", which means to extract the contents of page 1, page 4 to 15, page 2 and page 56 in sequence. If the number before "-" is greater than the number after "-", it means reverse order processing. For example: "300-1" means to extract the content of pages 300, 299, 298... 3, 2, and 1. Negative numbers indicate the number of pages in the last document, for example, "-1" means the first page from the bottom, and "1--2" means from the first page to the second last page. Semicolon ";" means split into multiple files, for example "1-5;1,6-10" means split into two files, where pages 1 to 5 are one file, pages 1 and 6 to 10 page is the second file.
